    • Method Detail

      • allOf

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T> CompletionStage<Collection<T>> allOf(CompletableFuture<T>... futures)
        Given an array of futures all of of the same type, returns a new CompletionStage that is completed with the result of all input futures when all futures are complete. The order of elements in the returned collection reflect the order of the elements in futures. If an element of futures completes exceptionally, so too will the CompletionStage returned by this method.
        Parameters:
        futures - an array of CompletableFuture all of type T
        Returns:
        a CompletionStage which will complete with a collection of the elements produced by futures when all futures complete
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if futures or any of it elements are null
        See Also:
        CompletableFuture.allOf(CompletableFuture[])

      • allOf

        public static <T> CompletionStage<Collection<T>> allOf(Collection<? extends CompletionStage<T>> stages)
        Given a collection of stages all of the same type, returns a new CompletionStage that is completed with the result of all input stages when all stages are complete. If the input collection has a defined order, the order will be preserved in the returned collection. If an element of stages completes exceptionally, so too will the CompletionStage returned by this method.
        Parameters:
        stages - a Collection of CompletionStage all of type T
        Returns:
        a CompletionStage which will complete with a collection of the elements produced by stages when all stages complete
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if stages or any of it elements are null

      • keyedAll

        public static <K,V> CompletionStage<Map<K,V>> keyedAll(Map<K,? extends CompletionStage<V>> stageMap)
        Given a Map from some key type K to CompletionStages of values, returns a CompletionStage which completes with a Map<K, V> when all the CompletionStages in the input map have completed. For example, if we have an asynchronous method to lookup student grade point averages. 
         
 Map<Student, CompletionStage<Double>> gpaFutures =
  students
      .stream()
      .collect(Collectors.toMap(Functions.identity(), student -> getGpaAsync(student));
 Map<Student, Double> studentGpas = keyedAll(gpaFutures).toCompletableFuture().join();
        If a value in stageMap completes exceptionally, so too will the CompletionStage returned by this method.
        Type Parameters:
        K - the input and output key type
        V - the value type for the map that will be produced by the returned CompletionStage
        Parameters:
        stageMap - a Map with keys of type K and CompletionStages of type V for values
        Returns:
        a CompletionStage that will be completed with a map mapping keys of type K to the values returned by the CompletionStages in stageMap

      • collect

        public static <T,A,R> CompletionStage<R> collect(Collection<? extends CompletionStage<T>> stages,
                                                 Collector<? super T,A,R> collector)
        Applies a collector to the results of all stages after all complete, returning a CompletionStage of the collected result. There is no need nor benefit for the Collector to have the CONCURRENT characteristic, the collector will be applied in a single thread. If any of the input stages completes exceptionally, so too will the CompletionStage returned by this method.
        Type Parameters:
        T - The type of the elements in stages which will be collected by collector
        A - The intermediate collection type
        R - The final type returned by collector
        Parameters:
        stages - a Collection of stages all of type T
        collector - a Collector which will be applied to the results of stages to produce the final R result.
        Returns:
        a CompletionStage which will complete with the R typed object that is produced by collector when all input stages have completed.
